SubTopics: Evaluate how magnets cause changes in the motion and position of objects, even when the objects are not touching the magnet.
Content: Students placed two sets of identical magnets near each other, as shown in the Before diagram. The After diagram shows that the magnets in the first set moved toward each other. The magnets in the second set did not move toward each other.
problems/TN20G3S/media/1a.jpg
Which statement b͟e͟s͟t explains the behavior of one of these sets of magnets?

A.Choice: The magnets in the first set moved toward each other because the opposite poles of the magnets attracted each other.

B.Choice: The magnets in the second set did not move toward each other because the distance between the magnets was too large.

C.Choice: The magnets in the first set moved toward each other because the north pole of each magnet was stronger than its south pole.

D.Choice: The magnets in the second set did not move toward each other because these magnets need electricity to work.

SubTopics: Explain how changes to an environment's biodiversity influence human resources.
Content: Fishery departments set catch limits on fish. Catch limits tell people how many fish they can keep each day.
How are catch limits good for people?

M.Choice: Catch limits cause the biodiversity in the oceans to go down.

P.Choice: Catch limits cause the price of fish at local stores to go up.

R.Choice: Catch limits allow for invasive species to move into the ecosystem.

S.Choice: Catch limits ensure that there will be a steady food source in the future.

SubTopics: Design solutions to reduce the impact of natural hazards (fires, landslides, earthquakes, volcanic eruptions, floods) on the environment.
Content: The picture shows a building that has special features. These features help keep the building from falling down during an earthquake.
problems/TN20G3S/media/7a.jpg

B.Choice: a square shape so that the building will not roll during an earthquake

SubTopics: Describe and compare the physical properties of matter including color, texture, shape, length, mass, temperature, volume, state, hardness, and flexibility.

P.Choice: The length of Block C is 3 centimeters.

R.Choice: The mass of Block C is greater than the mass of Block D.

S.Choice: The volume of Block C is greater than the volume of Block B.

T.Choice: The mass of Block C is the same as the masses of Block A and Block B together.

SubTopics: Explain the cause and effect relationship between a naturally changing environment and an organism's ability to survive.
Content: A student learns that the temperatures are getting warmer on Earth. The student claims that warmer temperatures are bad for polar bears.
Which polar bear action supports the student's claim?

A.Choice: The bears build dens in the same place.

B.Choice: The bears move to colder areas to find ice.

C.Choice: The bears change fur color to find a mate.

D.Choice: The bears produce more cubs in warmer seasons.

SubTopics: Design solutions to reduce the impact of natural hazards (fires, landslides, earthquakes, volcanic eruptions, floods) on the environment.
Content: A diagram of a mountainside is shown. Builders want to construct a new neighborhood in the area marked on the diagram.
problems/TN20G3S/media/12a.jpg
Which t͟h͟r͟e͟e solutions will b͟e͟s͟t reduce the threat of landslides for the new neighborhood?

M.Choice: Place pipes under the new neighborhood to drain water away.

P.Choice: Use machines to make the stream flow away from the houses.

R.Choice: Add plants that have wide and deep root systems.

S.Choice: Form a hill at the bottom of the slope.

SubTopics: Apply scientific ideas to design, test, and refine a device that converts electrical energy to another form of energy, using open or closed simple circuits.
Content: A student builds a circuit with a fan, a battery, and some wire. The battery is being drained too quickly.
problems/TN20G3S/media/13a.jpg
Which of these should the student add to the circuit so the battery drains more slowly?

A.Choice: a switch, so the fan can be turned on and off

B.Choice: a lightbulb, to show when the battery is getting low

C.Choice: a different battery that provides less energy

D.Choice: a different fan that requires more power

SubTopics: Recognize that energy is present when objects move; describe the effects of energy transfer from one object to another.
Content: A student rolls a ball down a ramp that has a toy car sitting at the bottom. The ball hits the car at the bottom. The car rolls off the ramp and onto the floor.
problems/TN20G3S/media/15a.jpg
The student wants to make the car roll farther and faster. In which of these ways can the student give the car more energy?

A.Choice: Use a different ball that weighs less.

B.Choice: Tape a small weight to the top of the car so it is heavier.

C.Choice: Use a taller ramp that raises the ball higher off the ground.

D.Choice: Make the bottom of the ramp longer so the ball has to roll farther before hitting the car.

SubTopics: Use tables, graphs, and tools to describe precipitation, temperature, and wind (direction and speed) to determine local weather and climate.

M.Choice: Months J, K, and L are the summer months.

P.Choice: Months Q, R, and S are the winter months.

R.Choice: Months N and O are summer months but Month P is not.

S.Choice: Months M and N are summer months but Month O is not.

T.Choice: Months Q and R are winter months but Month S is not.

SubTopics: Construct an argument to explain why some animals benefit from forming groups.
Content: Elephants live in groups called herds. A student claims that living in herds helps elephants survive. The picture shows larger elephants in a herd surrounding a young, small elephant.
problems/TN20G3S/media/21a.jpg
How does the elephant behavior shown support the student's claim?

A.Choice: The larger elephants in the herd step on the smaller elephant.

B.Choice: The larger elephants in the herd keep the smaller elephant from eating food.

C.Choice: The larger elephants in the herd protect the smaller elephant from predators.

D.Choice: The larger elephants in the herd can get to water more easily than the smaller elephant can.

SubTopics: Explain the cause and effect relationship between a naturally changing environment and an organism's ability to survive.
Content: A healthy pond ecosystem is shown in the picture.
problems/TN20G3S/media/24a.jpg
A scientist predicts that the pond will dry up and fill with sandy soil. Which t͟w͟o organisms will m͟o͟s͟t͟ ͟l͟i͟k͟e͟l͟y survive the change?

M.Choice: The fish will survive because it will be able to breathe air with its gills.

P.Choice: The frog will survive because it will be able to move to another pond.

R.Choice: The snail will survive because it will learn to eat minerals from the soil.

S.Choice: The water plants will survive because they will learn to live on land.

T.Choice: The duck will survive because it will be able to find food to eat in another area.
